Regression and model validation

The second week of the course has taken me through some data wrangling and later a little of analysis, with emphasis on graphical analysis.

Here we see some aspecsts of the data we start to work on. The data is gathered in 2014 from an introductory course on social statistics. The data consists of 7 variables and 166 observations, with the first variable being only the subject id. The variables are named so that one knows what one is dealing with for the most part, but for the variables Attitude, Deep, stra, surf and points a little clarification is necessary.

Attitude, Deep, stra and surf are all combined from several questionnaire variables with ranges 1-5, scaled so that the range of the sum is also 1-5 (by taking the mean). Points is the score of the final exam, ranging from 7 to 33, with maximum points Attitude is quite clear, Deep means deep, stra and surf the deep, strategid and surface type of approac to learning in the course.

Here we see a detailed graphical representation of the data. Some interesting facts pop up, namely most of the subjects are female. The ranges and the distributions of the variables are evident, and the most interesting fact about them is that the distributions of the attitude and surf variables differ between males and females. Some of the correlations between the variables seem possibly significant, but one cannot really say based on this analysis.

Statistical analysis

For a more detailed analysis, we fir a linear regression model onto the data. In the model we assume that the relationship of explanatory variables (here Attitude, stra and surf) explain the variable of interest (Points) in a linear manner.

library(ggplot2)
library(GGally)

# create a regression model with multiple explanatory variables
my_model2 <- lm(Points ~ Attitude + stra + surf, data = Learning)

# print out a summary of the model
summary(my_model2)

The statistical test (looking at the T-values and p-values) asks if the null hypothesis that the linear coefficient corresponding to the particular explanatory variable is zero. This would mean that the variable has little or no effect on the variation of the target variable, or Points in this case.

As seen from the summary, the coefficients related to stra and surf are not statistically significant and the variables should therefore be excluded from the model.

Redoing the model, this time with only the one (significant) explanatory variable:

library(ggplot2)
library(GGally)

# create a regression model with one explanatory variable
my_model2 <- lm(Points ~ Attitude, data = Learning)

# print out a summary of the model
summary(my_model2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = Points ~ Attitude, data = Learning)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -16.9763  -3.2119   0.4339   4.1534  10.6645 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  11.6372     1.8303   6.358 1.95e-09 ***
## Attitude      3.5255     0.5674   6.214 4.12e-09 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 5.32 on 164 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1906, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1856 
## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

From the renewed model we see that the relevant estimate of the coefficient is approximately 3,5. This means that Attitude toward the course explains the course grade (specifically, the total points) so that an increase of one in Attitude will lead to an increase of 3,5 in Points. The intercept parameter is the value of expected points in the exam with an attitude of expected attitude (generally the mean).

The multiple R squared of the model is in this case simply the square of the regression between Attitude and Points. Since it is around 0,2, approximately 20% of the variation of points can be explained by the variation of Attitude.

Model validation

Now we look at our model in light of some statistical graphical representations.

The assumptions of the model are that the error terms are approximately normally distributed with mean 0 and identical variation, uncorrelated and independent of the variable of interest. Specifically, the size of the error should not depend on the value of the explanatory or interesting variables.

From these pictures it seems that the model assumptions are approximately correct, with the small exception of small and large values of Points corresponding to some larger deviation from the estimated mean. Also, a couple of observations seem to have somewhat large leverages, but overall the assumptions of the model seem to hold quite well. Questionable is the ends of the spectrum, and additional analysis is needed.

The data consists of 36 variables and 382 observations. The first column X is only the identification number for the data. The data is gathered from two schools with a questionnaire to students and school reports and wrangled so that only students who studied both mathematics and portuguese are included.

We are interested in the link between alcohol consumption (specifically binary response, high or low) and some other interesting variables. Specifically, we will look at the variables “absences”, “health”, “sex” and “G3”, which means the mean final grade of math and portuguese of the student in question.

The basic assumptions are clear: high alcohol consumption could have an increasing effect on absences, a decreasing effect on health, sex could well have an effect on consumption (either way, but mostly women tend to drink less) and finally, the final grade should sink if one consumes a lot.

Looking at the distribution of the sex variable, we see what was assumed: women consume slightly less. Now let’s draw a more detailed plot of what’s going on in the variables.

From the graphs we see that the assumptions made previously seem somewhat correct; the correlation between alc_use and G3 is negative, especially in men, while the correlation between absences and alc_use is positive. Health does not seem to have a significant relation to alc_use, probably because the effects of alcohol use do not onset until later. Interestingly, all the distributions (on the diagonal) of the variables seem to be similar fo the sexes, except for alcohol consumption, which is significantly more skewed to the left for women. This leads to the question of validity: do the students answer differently based on sex?

3. The logit model

We will now fit a logistic model to the data.

## Waiting for profiling to be done...
##                    OR     2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.3260597 0.1046920 0.9862794
## G3          0.9284223 0.8648509 0.9957691
## absences    1.0972091 1.0509220 1.1503430
## health      1.0410775 0.8780964 1.2380464
## sexM        2.6365084 1.6462472 4.2800640

Here we see the summary of the fitted logistic regression model. The odds ratio for G3 is 0.9 with the confidence interval not overlapping 1 with 95% confidence. This means that odds for high G3 values mean lower odds for alcohol consumption. For absences, the odds ratio is a little over 1, wiht the confidence interval again not containing 1. This means that statistically the higher the absences, the higher the consumption of alcoho. For health we see what previously was seen; the confidence interval contains 1, which means that statistically we cannot be sure if health has any effect, and last but not least, the odds ratio for males compared to odds ratio of high alcohol consumption seems to be the highest in this model. This does not mean that sex is the best bet for understanding high alcohol consumption. It only states that the probability of being male seems to give some information on alcohol consumption.

Further analysis is needed if one wants to find out the best fit model for this data.

4. The goodness of the model

Looking at our model we decide that since health was not seemingly statistically significant, we leave it out of the model and test the predictive power of the model

\[\begin{equation*} log(\frac{p}{1-p})=\alpha +\beta_1 x_{G3} +\beta_2 x_{Abs} +\beta_3 x_{Sex} + \epsilon \end{equation*}\]

Where the coefficients correspond to the normal odds ratio and the odds ratios of G3, Abs and Sex, respectively.
